slides.title: The Mobilization Against the French Intelligence Bill of 2015 - by Félix Tréguer
slides.text:
In France, advocacy against Internet surveillance has historically been underdeveloped compared to countries such as the US, the UK or Germany.  But in late-2013 --that is, a few weeks after the beginning of the Snowden disclosures--, a failed mobilization against the legalization of the access of intelligence agencies to metadata pushed civil society groups to broker new connections. 

By the time the Intelligence Bill was introduced in Parliament, in March 2015, post-Snowden contention had finally come to fruition in France. 

During the three-month long parliamentary debate on the Bill (April-June 2015), advocacy groups and lawyers organizations were able to lead the opposition to the Bill, while benefiting from the support of a variety of other actors.

slides.title: Foreword: Categorizing the actors engaged in post-Snowden contention
slides.text:
A taxonomy was applied to categorize the different nodes of the network and help understand the diversity of contentious actors mobilized against the Intelligence Bill.

To activate the taxonomy, click on "Legend" in the bottom-left corner of the graph area.

For each of the slides, you can zoom in and out, and click-and-drag to explore the network and its actors.

slides.title: Advocacy groups, lawyers, unions
slides.text:
The mobilization of NGOs was quick and effective. 

OLN led the way in allowing joint analysis and direct action between human rights advocates (LDH, FIDH, etc.), digital rights activists (LQDN) and lawyers' associations (Syndicat des avocats de France}, Syndicat de la Magistrature, etc.). 

OLN held a joint press conference in late-March, put together a campaign website (sous-surveillance.fr), organized a couple of street demonstrations (attended by only a few hundred supporters, but that was enough to provide an illustration of what was going on online). A phone-call and email campaign was also launched by LQDN and several other activist groups (LQDN reports close to a thousand calls passed through its online VOIP tool).

Collectively, these groups succeeded in providing framing --and supporting legal analysis-- of the Bill as a authorizing forms of "mass surveillance."

slides.title: French NGOs receive international support
slides.text:
French civil society groups gathered support from leading international human rights organization like Amnesty and Human Rights Watch, whose French chapters took an active role in the opposition to the Bill. 

Digital rights international networks also mobilized in solidarity (EFF, EDRi, ACCESS, etc.), understanding the importance of the French case as one of the first post-Snowden and large-scale attempt at legalizing mass surveillance.

slides.title: Hackers & counter-measure providers
slides.text:
Another constituency mobilized against the Bill was a community of cryptography and transnational free software organizations and activist groups (TOR, Tails, etc. --bottom left), as well as the French community Internet service providers (under the umbrella organization "Fédération French Data Network" --bottom right).

These actors feature a strong technical know-how and a hacker (sometimes anarchist) political ethos. 

They relayed and sometimes directly contributed to the campaign of advocacy groups, providing technical expertise. Their Free Software, decentralized and encryption services were also framed as non-profit, privacy-enhancing counter-measures to surveillance.

slides.title: Tech industry & digital entrepreneurs
slides.text:
Digital entrepreneurs added business argument against the Bill by framing human rights infringements as a deterrent for international clients as well as for research and development. 

"The Independent,'' as we might call them, ranged from hosting providers and domain name registration services (like OVH and Gandi) to Software-as-a-Service startups, all of which have connections with Free Software aactivist circles, digital rights NGO and institutions like the French Digital Council.

slides.title: The campaign of digital entrepreneurs
slides.text:
The Independents' campaign against the Intelligence Bill was named "Ni piegons, ni espions''. Their campaign website relayed their petition against the Bill --which gathered support of almost a thousand other small companies-- as well as protest calls.

But what about Silicon Valley firms and their French competitors? Trade group like ASIC (whose members include Google and Microsoft),  also mobilized, but much less vocally than they had against the Military Planning Act in 2013. To the contrary of the full-fledged contention waged in the US or the UK, big US technology firms like Google or Microsoft declined to engage in the French debate, perhaps out of fear for being cornered for their double-speak on privacy and antagonizing even more French officials. 

As for their large French competitors, like Orange, SFR and others, their even greater dependence on and proximity with the state political elite ensured they would remain neutral bystanders.

slides.title: Scientists, academia, experts
slides.text:
Social scientists and computer experts also played a crucial role in validating the political and technical arguments put forward by activist groups. 

In late-April, a leading computer research institute, the INRIA, even took a very unusual move by publishing a brief denouncing technical ineffectiveness and risk of abuse associated with Big Data surveillance.

Experts specialized in intelligence matters (Zone d'Intérêt, former intelligence officers like Aboud Jaffar, Claude Moraes, antiterrorist judge Marc Trévidic) and the President of the Cryptographers' Reserve also contested the Bill.

slides.title: Human rights institutions
slides.text:
Both national and international institutional actors played a important role in bringing certification to the Intelligence Bill's critics, supplying legal analysis and influencing the parliamentary debate.

International organizations critical of the Bill included the Commissioner for Human Rights at the Council of Europe, Nils Muižnieks, who wrote a letter to French Senators ahead of their vote on the Bill, pointing to the wide scope of the text and the lack of oversight. The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) voiced similar its concerns through its Representative on Freedom of the Media, Dunja Mijatović. The Human Rights Council of the United Nations also criticized the Bill in its periodic review of human rights in France in June.

At the national level, the CNIL (data protection authority), the CNCDH (human rights watchdog) and the French Digital Council also logically certified the claims of NGOs. It was however more unusual to see former conservative politician Jacques Toubon, now holding the chair of ombudsman ("Défenseur des droits"), or Jean-Marie Delarue, a high-profile public servant and then-sitting President of the oversight commission for communications intellitence, publicly sharing their concerns. Other institutional opponents included several MPs that actively fought against the Bill in the Parliament.

slides.title: Alternative and mainstream media
slides.text:
Alternative media and journalists helped feed the contention by reporting on parliamentary debates, relaying the analysis of contentious actors and framing it for broader audiences.

They included online publications specialized in Internet policy and tech news (Next INpact, Numerama, reflets.info), investigative newsrooms (Mediapart, Arrêt sur image) and mainstream outlets (Le Monde, Libération}, Telerama, Rue 89 and the more conservative Le Figaro or La Croix).

slides.title: International media pay attention
slides.text:
International mainstream media at the heart of the Snowden disclosures, such as The Guardian, also covered the debate on the French Bill. 

In late-March, The New York Times even published a Op-Ed entitled  "The French Surveillance State" which had a strong echo in France.

slides.title: Suspicionless surveillance becomes law of the land
slides.text:
Overall, contention played an important role in making barring amendments that would have given intelligence agencies even more leeway than originally afforded by the Bill. 

Whereas the government hoped for a "union sacrée" in favor of the Bill, contention managed to fracture the initial display of unanimity. MPs from across the political spectrum, including many among both socialist and conservative ranks, fought against the Bill. 

But this vocal minority was much too small to prevent the adoption of the Bill: In the end, the Bill was adopted with 438 votes in favor, 86 against and 42 abstentions at the National Assembly and 252 for, 67 against and 26 abstentions at the Senate. And in its ruling of July 23rd , the Constitutional Council validated the law.

slides.title: The End
slides.text:
This online narrative is an interactive excerpt from a paper entitled "From Deep State Illegality to Law of the Land: The Case of Internet Surveillance in France", presented at the 7th Biennial Surveillance & Society Conference (April 22nd 2016, Barcelona).
